{
    "word": "Tolerate",
    "definitions": [
        "To suffer to be, or to be done, without prohibition or hindrance; to allow or permit negatively, by not preventing; not to restrain; to put up with; as, to tolerate doubtful practices."
    ],
    "examples": [
        "Crying should not be tolerated in children.",
        "We tolerate them because property and liberty, to a degree, require that toleration."
    ],
    "etymology": "[L. toleratus, p. p. of tolerare, fr. the same root as tollere to lift up, tuli, used as perfect of ferre to bear, latus (for tlatus), used as p. p. of ferre to bear, and E. thole. See Thole, and cf. Atlas, Collation, Delay, Elate, Extol, Legislate, Oblate, Prelate, Relate, Superlative, Talent, Toll to take away, Translate.]"
}